1. Introduction to Jenkins & CI/CD

Jenkins is a leading open-source automation server used to implement Continuous Integration (CI) and Continuous Delivery (CD), allowing 
developers to automate the building, testing, and deployment of software. It is a Java-based, self-contained program that runs on Windows, 
Linux, macOS, and other Unix-like systems.

Core Function: It automates repetitive manual steps in the development lifecycle, accelerating delivery and improving software quality.
Pipeline as Code: Jenkins uses Jenkinsfile (using Groovy syntax) to define build, test, and deploy stages, allowing pipelines to be 
version-controlled.
Extensibility: With over 1,900+ community-contributed plugins, Jenkins integrates with practically every tool in the DevOps toolchain, including Docker, Kubernetes, Git, and various cloud services.Architecture: It operates on a master-agent (formerly master-slave) architecture, enabling distributed builds across multiple machines for faster execution.
Installation: It can be installed natively or via Docker for portability.

